        <div class="blog-post">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title">6th month checkup</h2>
            <p class="blog-post-meta">March 12th, 2018 by Mom</p>
            <p>Guy had his 6 month follow up on March 9th, 2018. He weighted 17lbs 13.5 oz. His height was 26” and his head width was 17”. Before his appointment I was provided a sheet that asked several questions about Guy in terms of his Fine Motor skills, Gross Motor skills, problem solving skills, etc… These questions are asked to make sure he is on the right track in terms of his growth and development. For the most part Guy seems to have all of these “skills” down. The only room for growth was in relation to picking certain items up or dropping a toy looking to where it fell. The provider stated that most boys Guy’s age is not very good at sitting up she stated that this is where most girls excel, but Guy was able to sit up very well leaving her impressed.</p>
            <p>In relation to food she stated that Guy was able to now have baby food 2-3x a day, which would start to decrease the amount of formula he s taking. She also stated it was okay to continue with the baby oatmeal. I spoke with her about how no matter what time he goes to bed he always seems to wake up at 230 or 3am. She recommends that I let him cry. Just like adults; babies can get on the same routine schedule; her example was how as adults we always wake up for work then when the weekend comes we hope to sleep in but cannot because our bodies are so used to waking up at the same time. Same situation here with Guy. She stated to let him cry for 10 minutes if he is still crying go check on him (temp, if he needs a diaper change) pat his bottom a little bit letting him know he is okay, but then leave the room (make sure it is a very quiet environment). This will take about 14 days to break him out of the habit, we have already started since Friday.</p>
            <p>During the visit I told the provider how Guy has been dealing with a rash. He has a drool rash on his face that has spread to his neck (very bad looking). Then he developed a rash on his stomach and then the following week it spread to his back. I had tried everything from Aveeno to Aquaphor. It seemed that nothing was working. At one point I was even concerned that it was the baby food since that was the only new element in Guy’s life, so we stopped the baby food for 3 days to see if his rash would clear. Upon examination the provider said that it was considered a “dry” rash located on his stomach and back AND of course the drool rash. She recommended that I give him a bath every other day, put hydrocortisone on him only at night, and then keep using the Aquaphor during the day to moisturize his skin.</p>
            <p>That night we started the hydrocortisone, today is Monday the 12th Guy’s skin looks the best it has in 2 weeks.</p>
            <p>Guy also obtained all the same vaccines from his 2 months and 4 months checkup except Hib. Guy of course did cry when he obtained the shots, but quickly reverted to his smiles.</p>
            <p>Guy is overall a very happy 6-month-old baby. He loves watching YouTube with his daddy in the morning before day care. When he gets fussy we put on music and he calms down especially when we play Bruno Mars. Guy loves to play in his bouncy seat as well as his little car. Sleeping on his tummy is a preference over sleeping on his back. Guy has officially perfected rolling over and has almost gotten down sitting up by himself. Guy should be teething soon (because he has been fussy and two he is chewing everything) we have started to feel and kind of see a little tooth coming in on the left side.</p>
