            <h2 class="blog-post-title">Two-month pediatrician visit</h2>
            <p class="blog-post-meta">November 9th, 2017 by Dad</p>
            <p>Today Mom took Guy for his two months pediatrician visit. He weighted 10lb, 5oz, had a length of 21.5cm, and a head circumference of 37cm. No idea why it was in metric and imperial.</p>
            <p>The doctor had been out on maternity leave, and up until this visit we only saw the nurse practitioner.</p>
            <p>We are getting concerned that he may have reflux due to his grunting and fussiness. He didn’t seem to have the overt symptoms the Dr. mentioned, but said he could have “silent” reflux where the symptoms aren’t present. It can cause him to grunt and squirm, which is something babies also do normally. The doctor said that babies have an open sphincter, but as they get bigger it gets smaller and will eventually close. The situation should eventually go away. If it gets worse or symptoms start she might start him on a trial of medicine.</p>
            <p>Mel was also concerned about the amount of congestion he had, but we had asked prior to the visit and she had recommended a humidifier, which had helped. Mel brought this up at the appointment and she also recommend and using a saline solution with this Nose Frida device for clearing his sinuses. She also indicated that if he did have reflux it could contribute to the congestion because it can reach his sinuses.</p>
            <p>We are currently feeding him 120ml, which the doctor was fine with and said we should only increase the amount if there were strong cues that he was hungry. The feeding cues can be confused with their desire to suck for comfort. Then we should only increment it by 5ml because if we increase it too much it could cause his stomach to expand to a degree that would cause discomfort.</p>
            <p>He was given the Rotavirus vaccine, orally. He also got shots for DTaP, Hib, Polio, Pneumococcal Conjugate, and his second round of Hep B. This was administered with two shots, one in each leg. Poor Guy.</p>
            <p>He won’t be going back to the Doctor until he is 4 months, hopefully.</p>
