        <div class="blog-post">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title">He Hates His Basinet</h2>
            <p class="blog-post-meta">October 5, 2017 by Dad</p>
            <p>The day that Guy was born I had an all hands mandatory meeting at work right before I got the call from Mel to come to the hospital. I found out that our company was being bought. Today our new CEO came in the office and held an introduction meeting. I had taken this week off, but due to the gravity of the situation I felt compelled to come in. Mel was nice enough to take care of Guy while I slept and I was able to get some decent sleep with the help of a Benadryl. I went into work at the normal time and I was able to go to the store after and get home by 2:45 PM.</p>
            <p>After feeling everything out and getting into our grove we are feeling comfortable having some visitors. When I got home we had a friend over and then Mel's mom came over for a little bit.</p>
            <p>So far it is just your typical baby stuff. Our main conflicts are trying to get him to sleep in his basinet without killing him and dealing with his spitups he never did before today.</p>
            <p>For his basinet, it is almost guaranteed that within minutes of putting him in it he can go to being asleep to crying. We’ve used this magical crying machine to wake him up when he goes to sleep while feeding. With my concerns about SIDS I’ve been stringent about straying from the ABCs (Alone, Back, Crib) to try to get him to sleep in it. The doctor did say we can try to put the mattress at a slight angle by putting something under the mattress. We tried that and it didn’t change anything. At least I’m hoping it will help with any reflex or gas discomfort.</p>
            <p>The second thing we tried was swaddling him. In my Internet reading it seemed OK but the concern was that you shouldn’t leave him in the basinet with a loose blanket, and if he gets out of his swaddle then it becomes a loose blanket. That wasn’t that effective either.</p>
            <p>In the hospital, they used to roll up towels and blankets to build a little bed that surrounded him and he had a Gel pillow. What we did was do something similar, we took three rolled up towels and put it under the fitted sheet to build a pillow and bed to surround him. This has made a significant difference. He is less fussy and will not start crying within minutes of putting him in there.  I am hoping that since it is under the sheets it will not significantly increase his risk of SIDS.</p>
            <p>We were starting to think it might have something to do with the basinet so we did an experiment where we put him in his crib (for the first time) to see if he reacts the same way. Which he did. On a side note, he looks hilariously tiny in his crib.</p>
            <p>He sleeps better in his pack and play, but that is always during the day and he might just have different sleep patterns. Also, since it is during the day we are there to watch him so we don’t follow the ABCs, so he is swaddled and has a blanket to sleep on. Although, he still does get fussy when we put him in and sometimes will cry. Just not to the extent or consistency of his basinet.</p>
            <p>We find he sleeps best if he is held or make an angled bed with some soft blankets or pillows, swaddled or not. We only do this while watching him. Even laying him down on his back on our bed without being swaddled or in blankets he reacts much better than laying him down in the crib. To be fair our bed has a nice cushion and soft sheet on it.</p>
            <p>Regarding the spit up, he has never spit up any significant amount ever since we have been taking care of him in the hospital until today. Mostly what I have seen is that he will close his mouth and it will ooze out and drip down his chin. I think this is mostly due to having the bottle in his mouth while he isn’t actively sucking (generally because he is going to sleep) so it just stays in his mouth when you take the bottle out.</p>
            <p>Today he had spit up a couple times. I did not see the first time, but the second time was when I was burping him after he randomly started crying while feeding him and it got all over him and me. Since I am so used to him not spiting up I am not really on guard for that. In this instance, this was the fastest I’ve ever seen him take his bottle, which I’ve read can cause reflux.</p>
            <p>I’m not particularly worried about it since 50% of babies spit up at least once a day. I’m mostly concerned because it started today and we have not made any significant changes. Just for convenience this isn’t a habit I want him to develop. We have been trying to find ways to help avoid reflux that we have been trying to implement for several days now. Particularly having him and the bottle at a 45-degree angle, having him sit up for a few minutes after the feeding, and to try to burp him well. We have been getting concerned that he might be having reflux but not spiting up, just from how he acts after a feeding. Sometimes arching his back and getting fussy if you lay him on his back after.</p>
            <p>We think it was just a bad feeding day in general for him. He had a few feedings under his goal amount of 55ml and it was his lowest daily amount since we’ve been tracking. Although he did do a breastfeeding, which makes it harder to track, but other days he has had more from the bottle and did breastfeeding.</p>
            <p>Tomorrow I am going to try to get him to reach him goal amount either every feeding or as a total for the day. I think I’m just going to try to be more stringent about following the planned corrections I listed above. Sometimes you get lazy when burping as he doesn’t seem to burp a lot. I also read that if you keep him at too much of an incline it can increase reflux.</p>
            <p>Just to note, I say “we” a lot. Between all the discussions we have had about different things it is hard to keep track so sometimes when I say we they might just be my own concerns.</p>
            <p>This started out being a update about nothing and has turned into one of the longer posts…</p>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-post">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title">First Pediatrician Visit</h2>
            <p class="blog-post-meta">October 4, 2017 by Dad</p>
            <p>Today was his first pediatrician visit. This is also the first time taking him in the car after his initial ride home. We put him in his seat and the car without any issue. We had purchased car window shades on Amazon after seeing how bright it was on the first ride home, although Mel was planning on purchasing something like that prior. I had put these up right before we left. They did an OK job, as it didn’t cover the whole window so it was still enough to shine right on him.</p>
            <p>Our pediatrician office is called Providence Pediatrics. Not knowing where this was or recognizing the street name we used the GPS. It was in the shopping center at the intersection of Ballantyne Commons and Johnston. Our GPS of course took us a weird way which left us guessing most of the way.</p>
            <p>There was not much to the visit. We filled out new patient paperwork, family history, medicines, allergies, etc.</p>
            <p>We then went back where the nurse weighed, measured, and took his cranial dimensions. Respectively, 3034g (6lb, 11oz), 48.9cm (19.25”), 30cm (13”). The nurse practitioner pretty much fired off all the major concerns when she came in. They sneeze, grunt, hiccup, shake their leg, have rapid inhaling, mouth twitching, and their eyes cross. All which is normal. She said they sleep 20 hours a day and just eat/drink, sleep, poop, and pee.</p>
            <p>We discussed his feeding, eating, and sleeping habits. Went over our concerns and questions. Which was mostly focused around him being extra fussing while sleeping in his basinet and how we should do his feeding when he seems hungry or is sleeping during his scheduled feeding time. What I got out of it is we should just stick to the schedule and everything is normal. Also, we can put his basinet at a slight angle which might help and not kill him in his sleep (which I was concerned about).</p>
            <p>The nurse practitioner showed us the growth tables. She prefaced it saying that the length readings can be inaccurate because it’s just hard to get a baby to sit still. Assuming his first measurement was inaccurate, he mostly correlated with the 50th percentile line in weight and length. Based on his first length on the growth charts I saw he was closer to 90th percentile.</p>
            <p>The last thing we discussed was taking Synagis, a medication that helps prevent RSV. Since Guy is premature during the start of RSV season and will be going to day care they recommend that he takes the medication. It is just administered at the pediatrician once a month for 5 months.</p>
            <p>It is funny, since he just had his first visit today his one month visit will be next week.</p>
            <p>Other than the pediatrician visit, just your normal new born baby stuff.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-post">
            <h2 class="blog-post-title">Finally Home</h2>
            <p class="blog-post-meta">October 3, 2017 by Dad</p>
            <p>Guy finally came home on October 1st, 2017, around noon.</p>
            <h2>The Day Before</h2>
            <p>That Saturday since we had plans to see a movie we deviated from our normal routine. We went to the hospital at our normal time to catch his 1100 feeding instead of leaving after we stayed until after his 1400 feeding. We got lunch in between.</p>
            <p>At this point we had $30.00 worth of food vouchers. Unfortunately, the only good places to eat is Chick-fil-a which has abbreviated hours and is closed on Saturday and Sunday, and the X-Ray café which pretty much only serves hamburgers. We decided to go to the cafeteria one last time for some bad food. We still have vouchers.</p>
            <p>When we got there his feeding tube was out, which we didn’t even notice at first. We were planning on breastfeeding Guy but they wanted him to try the bottles he would be using at home to get used to them. At home, we plan on using Dr. Brown’s bottles which the hospital provided us one for the feeding. It was recommended to us by the nurses in the NICU.</p>
            <p>We discussed some things for his discharge and the nurse showed us how to mix his formula. Both 100% formula or to supplement the pumped milk because they want him to have 24 calories per 30ml. She also showed how to dispense his Poly-Vi-Sol with Iron with these tiny syringes.</p>
            <p>They also told us to bring a cooler because we had given them so much milk we actually exceeded the amount they normally store. We actually planned on bringing more the day we found out he was being discharged, but we forgot.</p>
            <p>That night he did his car seat test. They didn’t contact us about the result of this, so we assumed there weren’t any issues.</p>
            <h2>Leaving Day</h2>
            <p>On Sunday (October 1) they told us we can get to the hospital by the normal time and we should be out by noon. We still ended up getting their 30 minutes before we usually do, hoping we would get out earlier. At this point we knew he was going to be discharged today.</p>
            <p>When we got there, they wanted us to do is normal care at 1100 while the nurse Angela was working on the discharged paper work. They brought a cart that looks like a train and started filling it up with pretty much everything they had in the room for him that wasn’t nailed down. We got formula, diapers, paper towels, syringes, bottles, fancy formula water, and probably more than I’m forgetting.</p>
            <p>They also brought up all the milk they had stored. We only have two coolers and the lunch box we were using. One is huge and the other is a smaller one that holds 14 cans. Apparently, we had so much that they froze a bin and a half and they normally only have one bin per person. It did not fit in my cooler, so they had to provide us with an additional container.</p>
            <p>The doctor and the nurse practitioner stopped in and gave us some more details about Guy and the discharge. They warned us to be careful about avoiding interaction with others to prevent him from getting sick. Basically, to limit contact with visitors, ensure they have proper hand hygiene before coming in contact with the baby, and not letting anyone sick near the baby. She recommended to not let him out of the house until after the holidays, not even for the holidays. <strong>So please keep that in mind when asking about seeing the baby.</strong> Another important item they mentioned was that it is RSV season, which could be like a normal cold for us, it can be potentially fatal for the baby.</p>
            <p>They also had to verify from both of us that we thought it was OK for him to come home.</p>
            <p>Once we had all that packed up I went and pulled the car up to the front and they loaded him in to his car seat and brought him down. We loaded up the car and got him strapped in and drove off. Our doctors and nurses were amazing, but if I never step foot in that hospital again I will be very happy.</p>
            <h2>After coming home</h2>
            <p>I believe it has been your typical baby coming home experience. His feeding and diaper routine hasn’t really changed. Only issue is he really doesn’t like to sleep in his basinet, or crib. We think there must be something different about them from what he was used to in the hospital that he isn’t getting accustomed to. In the hospital, he had a clear, short walled basinet with a gel pillow and surrounded by rolled up towels, swaddled with the bed at an incline. Which is fine as he is watched 24 hours and monitored by machines. But to follow the ABC’s (Alone, Back, Crib) at home we just have him in his basinet with nothing but a onesie.</p>
            <p>That has made it quite a challenge to get him back to sleep for those late-night feedings.</p>
        </div>
